{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566509"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:42:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:42:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18837"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18837"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.76,0.02,0.04,0.07,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11570"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79639"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11570"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64943"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5744"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11282"},{"type":"tags","id":"11294"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27235"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79639"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA General Practitioner discovers that another doctor in town is offering a new cosmetic procedure at lower prices than their own practice. The General Practitioner makes a formal complaint to the Medical Board about the other doctor\u0027s competence, despite having no evidence of poor patient outcomes or safety concerns. The complaint emphasises that the other doctor\u0027s prices are \u0027suspiciously low\u0027 and suggests this must indicate substandard care.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this type of complaint?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vexatious complaint","Mandatory notification","Protected disclosure","Voluntary notification","Statutory complaint"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a \u003Cstrong\u003Evexatious complaint\u003C/strong\u003E - one made without merit and with an ulterior motive (protecting market share) rather than genuine patient safety concerns. The complaint lacks evidence of poor care and is motivated by commercial interests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMandatory notification\u003C/strong\u003E - These are legally required reports to the Australian Health Practitioner Regulation Agency (AHPRA) about serious concerns such as practising while intoxicated, sexual misconduct, significant departure from accepted standards, or placing the public at risk of harm due to impairment. This scenario does not involve any such issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtected disclosure\u003C/strong\u003E - This refers to whistleblowing about serious misconduct that is protected under Australian legislation such as the Public Interest Disclosure Act. It requires genuine belief of wrongdoing and protection of public interest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVoluntary notification\u003C/strong\u003E - Voluntary notifications can be made to Ahpra about potential risks to patient safety or professional misconduct but must be based on reasonable\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ebelief of substandard care, which is absent in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStatutory complaint\u003C/strong\u003E - Statutory complaints are formal complaints made under healthcare legislation, such as to a health complaints commission, regarding violations of healthcare rights or standards. This complaint does not meet the criteria for a statutory complaint since there is no evidence of violations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaking vexatious complaints is itself unprofessional conduct that may result in regulatory action against the complaining practitioner. Healthcare practitioners should only raise concerns through appropriate channels when there are legitimate patient safety issues.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A vexatious complaint is one made without merit, with malicious intent, or for an ulterior purpose rather than genuine patient safety concerns.","Healthcare practitioners have a duty to report legitimate patient safety concerns through appropriate channels.","Making vexatious complaints about other health practitioners may result in regulatory action by the Medical Board of Australia."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64943"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18837"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64943"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T12:03:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T12:04:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11570"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79639"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"e